## Structure
Templates consist of different types of elements.

![](data:image/jpeg;base64,)

These elements can be simply arranged one after the other, e.g. first a picture element, then text elements, below data fields etc. However, they can also be nested within each other, for example in tables containing cell elements that contain text elements.

The structure follows the XSL-FO standard. Therefore, most elements are contained in **blocks**, e.g. a text element is always necessarily located in a block. Template content that needs to be **underneath **each other, should be located in separate blocks.

![](data:image/png;base64,)

Template contents that should be **next **to each other, i.e. in the same line, should be located in the same block.

![](data:image/jpeg;base64,)

From a technical point of view, a distinction is made between block-level elements (they are underneath each other) and inline-elements (can be in the same block and thus stand next to each other). Inline elements such as texts, images, links, or data fields must always be located in one block. Some elements such as tables, conditions, repetitions or comments can be block-level elements or inline elements.

For better structuring, **Containers **can also be used if blocks should be combined into a group for easier assignment of formats or other properties.

Since all elements are arranged on pages, they are subordinated to them. Therefore, the topmost element of the hierarchy is always "Page Sequence", which contains at least one "Page Content" element containing the document body elements assigned to the respective layout. The elements of the static layout regions (header, footer as well as left and right margins) are located in sibling nodes to the page content.

![](data:image/jpeg;base64,)

Page Number, page break: If the template contains more content than it will fit on a single print page, the editor displays the page extended. Since the number of pages of the actual output document depends on several factors, especially on the dynamic content, the template in the editor is displayed without page breaks. The output document automatically has as many pages as necessary. For details on page management see [Page break, page settings, page master.](/doxee-platform/docs/6-6-business-designer-user-guide-page-break-page-settings-page-master-1)

## Text elements, text editing
When you write text in your template, a text element is automatically created inside a block. The block stands for the paragraph, the text element for content.

A text element can contain a single letter or a text of any length. Within a text element there is an automatic line break. As soon as you press Enter during text input, a new text element is automatically created in a new block.

![](data:image/jpeg;base64,)

If it is necessary to write the text in a new line without creating a new paragraph/block, you can use the Alt code 0010 (hold Alt key, enter 0010 code on the numeric keypad, release Alt key).

> Note:

*Only possible on keypads with a numeric block*

Tabulators do not exist - the tab key has no function in texts. Spacing or different alignments within a line should be created using tables - see [Tables](/doxee-platform/docs/6-6-business-designer-user-guide-tables-1).

Text editing:

You can overwrite text by selecting it first.

To cut, copy and paste text you can use the Ctrl+X, Ctrl+C, Ctrl+V keyboard commands.

It is also possible to paste text copied from other programs (e.g. MS Word).

## Create elements (insert elements)
To insert an element, simply drag the respective symbol from the palette to the desired position in the template.

![](data:image/jpeg;base64,)

You can create text elements by simply entering text directly into the template.

## Marking elements
Attention when editing elements - e.g. when moving or formatting - make sure that you really select the desired element. The best way to do this is via **Outline**, where you can simply click on the desired element.

To mark elements in the editor directly on the template you must click on the **frame **of the element to select it (preferably on the bottom frame line). You will then see the element name at the top right of the element frame.

To mark text elements, you can place the cursor somewhere in the text.

![](data:image/png;base64,)

To select a block, click on a free space next to the content (inside the page margin).

![](data:image/png;base64,)

## Delete elements
To delete an element, it is best to select it in the outline - or you can click on the element frame in the editor - then use the Del key or Backspace.

## Move and copy elements
To **move **elements, it is best to use the outline. Here you can simply drag elements to the desired position. A horizontal line indicates the new position **between **the existing elements. If you want to place inline elements, e.g. texts, next to each other, you must make sure that you release it **next **to the respective element when moving.

![](data:image/jpeg;base64,)

This way you can also nest elements within each other: If you drag an element **on top **of another element, it will be integrated into the element, provided that it is possible for the respective element type.

**Copying **and inserting of elements is only possible in the editor directly in the template. Here you can use the keyboard shortcuts Ctrl+C, Ctrl+V.

When inserting elements, you must first place the cursor in the correct position - between two existing elements - preferably by first clicking on the previous element and then moving the cursor between the two elements using the arrow keys.

The options for copying and moving contents depend on the block, the element structure and on the element type. Use the keyboard shortcuts in the editor. Only in the outline you can move elements by dragging them. Moving several elements at the same time is only possible if they are located in the same block or container.

> Note:

*Always make sure that the structure of the template contents is "clean" and logically correct, e.g. that continuous text is not unnecessarily divided into several text elements and the like.*

## Element specific commands
Depending on the element type there can be a context menu which you mouse over the element or exactly over the element symbol.

![](data:image/png;base64,)![](data:image/png;base64,)

## Undo editing
With the key combination Ctrl+Z or with the *Undo *button on the "floating toolbar" you can undo as many editing steps as you like.
